<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>EFRA Committee Food Security Inquiry – Written Evidence submitted by Food Security Ltd</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Written Evidence submitted by Food Security Ltd</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">We are a group of concerned farmers who want to alert Government and the public to the rapid decline in the amount of food produced in this country, and to the fact </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">that defence and national security are inextricably linked with home food production.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">We are not anti-government, neither are we commercially or politically motivated. We are particularly concerned about how 62m people will be fed in the event of a crisis,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> and what can actually be done to improve this critical situation.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Vast improvements could be set in motion by having a dynamic strategy to start becoming a net exporter of food, like the USA, rather than being complacent in policies and attitude to being</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> merely 60-62% self-sufficient in our food production. With limited agricultural land, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">for one thing, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">could it be a very sensible policy for solar panels to be located on roofs rather than in potentially food-producing fields?</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The p</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">rice of food is bound to</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> be volatile, depending on supplies available, but the Prince of Wales’ passion to attract young people into farming and food supply will not be realized if farm incomes are not reasonable. He seems concerned about fair prices needing to be paid by superma</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">rkets; what about the record UK farm borrowings and the peak number of approaches by farmers to charities that have been set up to help them?</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Retailers must adapt their practices to change the fine balance of risk and reward throughout the food chain. At p</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">resent, by far the major risk is taken by the food producer.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Volatility in global food supply and demand does leave the UK vulnerable to price spikes and shortages. It is surely a massive responsibility of this Government to have food available for its 62m</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> people in bad and critical times as well as in easy times, during which planning should be prime- in view of not only the ‘perfect storm’ ahead, but also the hugely important need of sufficient food being grown within its shores to maintain defence of thi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s island nation in any forthcoming crisis.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">   Any increase of reliance on imports of food and food production inputs such as fertilizer increases the susceptibility of these</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">supplies to pressures outside of our control.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Science, as ever, will be indispensib</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">le in the feeding of our growing population. To quote Lord de Mauley,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> ‘Agri-technologies have the potential to transform food production in Britain. Demand for food is rising rapidly and time is not on our side. We have a world class science and technolog</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">y sector. Breakthroughs in nutrition, genetics, and precision farming mean the sector is one of the world’s fastest growing and exci</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ting markets. Now we need to ens</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ure this innovation is converted into practical tools that deliver in the field.’ </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">To move </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">forward with science and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">G M</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> technology is another plank in improved UK food security.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">There is a need for greater investment in R and D to reverse the decline in agricultural and horticultural  productivity growth.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">It has been observed globally that a dro</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">p in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">such investment has been linked to a decline in agricultural productivity.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The current systems for traceability have proved</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> their worth in events such as foot and mouth outbreaks, TB and the horse-meat scandal. Issues relating to ‘farm to plate’ large</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ly centre on transport factors – food miles etc. – with the obvious benefits of growing much more of our food in the UK. Is there too much complacency about t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">he circa 2K refrigerated lorries </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> entering</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> the UK via</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Dover Harbour each day, for example?</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Further</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> as to traceability, what should be done about our lax animal disease control at our airports and docks? Compare entry into the USA or Australia, where there is a dynamic protection of their agriculture and food industry.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">While it is acknowledged that the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">largest climate change risk may not be in the UK, a ‘let’s import our food’ strategy would be largely blind to risks elsewhere; the question must be asked as to how ethical it is to import food from countries where people are malnourished and where water i</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s scarce.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Phil Evans, Government Services Director at the Met Office, has said: ‘Weather has a real impact on farming</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and climate change will increase future pressure on production. The Met Office has a long history of translating its science to provide s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ervices to decision making. We hope this established expertise can be used to help the agricultural industry become more resilient’.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> We inevitably use up a large amount of scarce and precious water when we im</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">port any food from, say, Africa, where possibly </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the largest climate change risk exists.   </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> ‘UK food security strategies and planning’ – what does this phrase mean? What audits and risk assessments have been done across Whitehall? Is it currently left to Defra alone? Where and when do major departments s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">uch as Defence and the Treasury get a say? Consider that from 1970-1974 there was the ‘Ministry of Agriculture, Fisheries and Food, Defence, Emergencies and Crop Improvement Division’. Surely the question of our secure food supply should also be a matter f</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">or the National Security Council.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Food producers, including small farmers, are struggling to maintain production; most would have no hope of increasing it. The recent and pertinent words of the Committee’</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Chair, answer this issue succinctly: ‘Against a b</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ackground where farm incomes are falling, the Government needs to recognize that cutting payments to these businesses will reduce their ability to compete in the marketplace, will leave farmers less able to invest in vital infrastructure and may make them </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">more vulnerable to shocks such as poor weather, higher input costs and price variations’. Also, the Committee has warned against ‘Government plans to transfer more money away from direct payments to farmers by shifting it towards environmental schemes’.  H</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">as anyone assessed how much higher a UK family’s food bill would have been by now if there had been no CAP payments to UK farmers in the last, say, 7 years? </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The notion commonly held by the public that the CAP puts up the price we pay for our food needs era</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">dicating once and for all.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">To have an increasingly vibrant and economically sustainable food producing industry is essential for UK food security, with all the important side-effects of securing the future of our rural communities, our environment, farming</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> businesses, food businesses, village facil</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ities and other rural </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">facilities. The grim fact of ever fewer farmers producing a commodity ever more cheaply needs addressing.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">  Our huge comparative advantage in being able to grow grass and turn it into milk and</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> meat  could well be exploited</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">; our large dependence on imports of butter and cheese could be greatly reduced by a concerted and strategic  push from high up to provide for the manufacturing of much more butter and cheese and dried milk. A country such as </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">China </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">has an insatiable demand for milk and milk products</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">-a fact currently making great earnings for New </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Zealand’s  economy.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Executive Summary</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">For several years we have voiced our concern about the UK food trade deficit. Has the Treasury noticed this </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ever-incre</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">asing gap – now £19.5</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">bn, up £5bn since 5 years ago? Should this fact not be a potent warning and a wake-up call?</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Ou</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">r</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> reliance on sea traffic is becoming gradually greater; however, no-one can deny the weakening of the Royal Navy. We also rely on </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">certain geo-political factors that do not change – trade, distance, and</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> choke points that the UK depends on. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">There is a large range and shifting complex of risks and threats to our national security, but one thing is clear, that to increase UK food product</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ion is essential and vital to our future safety as well as to our social and economic well-being.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> David Heath’s article in the national press ‘Dig for Survival’ was starkly relevant in our present position.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Our thoughts are tersely summed up in the words o</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">f George Washington: ‘I know of no pursuit in which more real and important services can be rendered to any country than by improving its agriculture’.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">December 2013 </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>